## Migration: `TimedExecutor` → .NET 8

**Pattern identified: Timeout enforcement** — `Thread.Abort()` kills a thread exceeding a time limit. In .NET 8, `Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` (`SYSLIB0006`).

### What breaks and why

| .NET Framework API | .NET 8 behavior |
|---|---|
| `Thread.Abort()` | Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | Never thrown — dead code |

### Migrated code

```csharp
public class TimedExecutor
{
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        return ExecuteWithTimeout(
            token => work(),   // wrap legacy work
            timeout);
    }

    // Preferred overload — work cooperates with cancellation
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<CancellationToken, T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);

        try
        {
            var task = Task.Run(() => work(cts.Token), cts.Token);
            return task.GetAwaiter().GetResult();
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
    }
}
```

### Key pitfalls

| Pitfall | Explanation |
|---|---|
| **Cancellation is cooperative, not preemptive** | Unlike `Thread.Abort()`, cancelling won't forcibly kill CPU-bound work. The `Func<T>` overload (no token) will let work run to completion even after timeout — the caller just stops waiting. Only the `Func<CancellationToken, T>` overload can actually stop work mid-flight. |
| **Must check the token inside work** | Pass the token through the full call chain. Insert `token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested()` at checkpoints in loops and between expensive operations. |
| **Dispose `CancellationTokenSource`** | It owns an internal timer — leaking it leaks the timer. Always `using`. |
| **`catch (OperationCanceledException)` replaces `catch (ThreadAbortException)`** | Use `when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)` to distinguish timeout from external cancellation. |
| **`Task.Run` uses the thread pool** | Unlike `new Thread()`, this reuses pool threads. If work does long blocking I/O, consider `Task.Factory.StartNew` with `TaskCreationOptions.LongRunning`. |

### Calling the new API

```csharp
var executor = new TimedExecutor();

// Legacy (fire-and-forget — work can't be stopped mid-flight):
var result = executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(
    () => ExpensiveCalculation(),
    TimeSpan.FromSeconds(5));

// Preferred (cooperative — work actually stops):
var result = executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(token =>
{
    foreach (var item in items)
    {
        token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested();
        Process(item);
    }
    return items.Count;
}, TimeSpan.FromSeconds(5));
```

### For truly uncooperative code

If work **cannot** be modified to check a token (e.g., third-party library, native call), the only reliable kill mechanism is `Process.Kill` — move the work to a child process. There is no in-process equivalent of `Thread.Abort` in modern .NET.
